In article <33bqea$lne@ccu2.auckland.ac.nz>,
Peter Gutmann <pgut1@cs.aukuni.ac.nz> wrote:
>Death rays from Mars made John K. Taber <jktaber@netcom.com> write:
>>OK, let me ask the dumb question.  What's wrong with extreme encryption, or in
>>other words, destruction of the data.  I mean something like a thermite
>>grenade built into the disk drive triggered with a panic button.
> 
>Because any attacker worth their salt will never let you get to the point of
>using the destruction mechanism.  In addition what's needed is the ability to
>protect, but also preserve, the information.  If what you're trying to keep
>secret are the complete business records for your company, then revealing them
>to an enemy may be preferable to destroying them altogether.

But if what you're trying to protect is the plans for the overthrow
of a totalitarian government then destroying them may be preferable
to leaving any chance of recovery by the goons.  In other words,
needs differ.

		--Ken Pizzini
